userInput: Will I lose coverage because of my asthma?

response.stringValue: Whether you have asthma, or another pre-existing condition, it's helpful to understand your health insurance rights

title.stringValue: Good news is, all individual and group (employer) plans must cover treatment for pre-existing medical conditions

response.stringValue: No insurance plan can legally reject you, charge you more, or refuse to pay for essential health benefits for any condition you had before your coverage started

title.stringValue: Can I tell you about coverage for a condition once you're already enrolled?

response.stringValue: Alright! Here you go — once you're enrolled, the plan can't deny you coverage or raise your rates based only on your health
Medicaid and the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) also can't refuse to cover you, or charge you more because of a pre- existing condition

title.stringValue: Would you like to know more about pregnancy, or the exception to this rule — grandfathered plans?

response.stringValue: A grandfathered plan is an insurance policy that was purchased on or before March 23, 2010. These plans were sold through insurance companies, agents, or brokers and may not include the protections that exist under the Affordable Care Act
Unfortunately, grandfathered plans don’t have to cover pre- existing conditions or preventive care. If a health plan is grandfathered, it must disclose this information

title.stringValue: Would you like me to tell you about what your options are if you have a grandfathered plan?

response.stringValue: If you have a grandfathered plan and want pre-existing conditions covered, you have 2 options:

➡️ You can switch to a Marketplace plan that will cover them during open enrollment
➡️ You can buy a Marketplace plan outside open enrollment when your grandfathered-plan year ends, and you’ll qualify for a special enrollment period
